# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: threat-hunting
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] An **advanced persistent threat** (**APT**) is a stealthy cybersecurity threat, typically manipulated by a state or state-sponsored group, which gains unauthorized access to a computer network and remains undetected for an extended period.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] In recent times, the term may also refer to non-state-sponsored groups conducting large-scale targeted intrusions for specific goals.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] Such threat actors' motivations are typically political or economic.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] Every major business sector has recorded instances of cyberattacks by advanced actors with specific goals, whether to steal, spy, or disrupt.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] These targeted sectors include government, defense, financial services, legal services, industrial, telecoms, consumer goods and many more.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] Some groups utilize traditional espionage vectors, including social engineering, human intelligence and infiltration to gain access to a physical location to enable network attacks.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] The purpose of these attacks is to install custom malware.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] APT attacks on mobile devices have also become a legitimate concern, since attackers are able to penetrate into cloud and mobile infrastructure to eavesdrop, steal, and tamper with data.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] The median "dwell-time", the time an APT attack goes undetected, differs widely between regions.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] FireEye reported the mean dwell-time for 2018 in the Americas as 71 days, EMEA as 177 days, and APAC as 204 days.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] Such a long dwell-time allows attackers a significant amount of time to go through the attack cycle, propagate, and achieve their objectives.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] Warnings against targeted, socially-engineered emails dropping trojans to exfiltrate sensitive information were published by UK and US CERT organisations in 2005.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] This method was used throughout the early 1990s and does not in itself constitute an APT.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] The term "advanced persistent threat" has been cited as originating from the United States Air Force in 2006 with Colonel Greg Rattray cited as the individual who coined the term.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] The Stuxnet computer worm, which targeted the computer hardware of Iran's nuclear program, is one example of an APT attack.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] In this case, the Iranian government might consider the Stuxnet creators to be an advanced persistent threat.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] Advanced persistent threat (APT) as a term may be shifting focus to computer-based hacking due to the rising number of occurrences.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] PC World reported an 81 percent increase from 2010 to 2011 of particularly advanced targeted computer attacks.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] Actors in many countries have used cyberspace as a means to gather intelligence on individuals and groups of individuals of interest.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] The United States Cyber Command is tasked with coordinating the US military's offensive and defensive cyber operations.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] Numerous sources have alleged that some APT groups are affiliated with, or are agents of, governments of sovereign states.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] A Bell Canada study provided deep research into the anatomy of APTs and uncovered widespread presence in Canadian government and critical infrastructure.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] Attribution was established to Chinese and Russian actors.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] In incidents analysed by Mandiant, the average period over which the attackers controlled the victim's network was one year, with longest – almost five years.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] The infiltrations were allegedly performed by Shanghai-based Unit 61398 of People's Liberation Army.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] Chinese officials have denied any involvement in these attacks.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] Previous reports from Secdev had previously discovered and implicated Chinese actors.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] There are tens of millions of malware variations, which makes it extremely challenging to protect organizations from APT.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] While APT activities are stealthy and hard to detect, the command and control network traffic associated with APT can be detected at the network layer level with sophisticated methods.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] Deep log analyses and log correlation from various sources is of limited usefulness in detecting APT activities.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] It is challenging to separate noises from legitimate traffic.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] Traditional security technology and methods have been ineffective in detecting or mitigating APTs.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] Active cyber defense has yielded greater efficacy in detecting and prosecuting APTs (find, fix, finish) when applying cyber threat intelligence to hunt and adversary pursuit activities.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] Human-Introduced Cyber Vulnerabilities (HICV) are a weak cyber link that are neither well understood nor mitigated, constituting a significant attack vector.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] Multiple organizations may assign different names to the same actor.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] As separate researchers could each have their own varying assessments of an APT group, companies such as CrowdStrike, Kaspersky, Mandiant, and Microsoft, among others, have their own internal naming schemes.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] Names between different organizations may refer to overlapping but ultimately different groups, based on various data gathered.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] CrowdStrike assigns animals by nation-state or other category, such as "Kitten" for Iran and "Spider" for groups focused on cybercrime.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] Other companies have named groups based on this system — Rampant Kitten, for instance, was named by Check Point rather than CrowdStrike.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] Dragos bases its names for APT groups on minerals.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] Mandiant assigns numbered acronyms in three categories, APT, FIN, and UNC, resulting in APT names like FIN7.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] Other companies using a similar system include Proofpoint (TA) and IBM (ITG and Hive).
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] Microsoft used to assign names from the periodic table, often stylized in all-caps (e.g.
[src:threat-hunting/advanced-persistent-threat] POTASSIUM); in April 2023, Microsoft changed its naming schema to use weather-based names (e.g.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] Such examples may arouse suspicions of being generated by a different mechanism, or appear inconsistent with the remainder of that set of data.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection finds application in many domains including cybersecurity, medicine, machine vision, statistics, neuroscience, law enforcement and financial fraud to name only a few.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] Anomalies were initially searched for clear rejection or omission from the data to aid statistical analysis, for example to compute the mean or standard deviation.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] They were also removed to better predictions from models such as linear regression, and more recently their removal aids the performance of machine learning algorithms.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] However, in many applications anomalies themselves are of interest and are the observations most desirous in the entire data set, which need to be identified and separated from noise or irrelevant outliers.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] Many attempts have been made in the statistical and computer science communities to define an anomaly.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] The concept of intrusion detection, a critical component of anomaly detection, has evolved significantly over time.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] Initially, it was a manual process where system administrators would monitor for unusual activities, such as a vacationing user's account being accessed or unexpected printer activity.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] This approach was not scalable and was soon superseded by the analysis of audit logs and system logs for signs of malicious behavior.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] By the late 1970s and early 1980s, the analysis of these logs was primarily used retrospectively to investigate incidents, as the volume of data made it impractical for real-time monitoring.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] The affordability of digital storage eventually led to audit logs being analyzed online, with specialized programs being developed to sift through the data.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] These programs, however, were typically run during off-peak hours due to their computational intensity.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] The 1990s brought the advent of real-time intrusion detection systems capable of analyzing audit data as it was generated, allowing for immediate detection of and response to attacks.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] This marked a significant shift towards proactive intrusion detection.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] As the field has continued to develop, the focus has shifted to creating solutions that can be efficiently implemented across large and complex network environments, adapting to the ever-growing variety of security threats and the dynamic nature of modern computing infrastructures.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection is applicable in a very large number and variety of domains, and is an important subarea of unsupervised machine learning.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] As such it has applications in cyber-security, intrusion detection, fraud detection, fault detection, system health monitoring, event detection in sensor networks, detecting ecosystem disturbances, defect detection in images using machine vision, medical diagnosis and law enforcement.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection was proposed for intrusion detection systems (IDS) by Dorothy Denning in 1986.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection for IDS is normally accomplished with thresholds and statistics, but can also be done with soft computing, and inductive learning.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] Types of features proposed by 1999 included profiles of users, workstations, networks, remote hosts, groups of users, and programs based on frequencies, means, variances, covariances, and standard deviations.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] The counterpart of anomaly detection in intrusion detection is misuse detection.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection is vital in fintech for fraud prevention.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] Preprocessing data to remove anomalies can be an important step in data analysis, and is done for a number of reasons.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] Statistics such as the mean and standard deviation are more accurate after the removal of anomalies, and the visualisation of data can also be improved.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] In supervised learning, removing the anomalous data from the dataset often results in a statistically significant increase in accuracy.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection has become increasingly vital in video surveillance to enhance security and safety.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] With the advent of deep learning technologies, methods using Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) and Simple Recurrent Units (SRUs) have shown significant promise in identifying unusual activities or behaviors in video data.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] These models can process and analyze extensive video feeds in real-time, recognizing patterns that deviate from the norm, which may indicate potential security threats or safety violations.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] An important aspect for video surveillance is the development of scalable real-time frameworks.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] Such pipelines are required for processing multiple video streams with low computational resources.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] In IT infrastructure management, anomaly detection is crucial for ensuring the smooth operation and reliability of services.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] These are complex systems, composed of many interactive elements and large data quantities, requiring methods to process and reduce this data into a human and machine interpretable format.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] Techniques like the IT Infrastructure Library (ITIL) and monitoring frameworks are employed to track and manage system performance and user experience.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] Detected anomalies can help identify and pre-empt potential performance degradations or system failures, thus maintaining productivity and business process effectiveness.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection is critical for the security and efficiency of Internet of Things (IoT) systems.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] It helps in identifying system failures and security breaches in complex networks of IoT devices.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] The methods must manage real-time data, diverse device types, and scale effectively.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] Garg et al. have introduced a multi-stage anomaly detection framework that improves upon traditional methods by incorporating spatial clustering, density-based clustering, and locality-sensitive hashing.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] This tailored approach is designed to better handle the vast and varied nature of IoT data, thereby enhancing security and operational reliability in smart infrastructure and industrial IoT systems.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection is crucial in the petroleum industry for monitoring critical machinery.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] A 2015 paper proposed a novel segmentation algorithm using support vector machines to analyze sensor data for real-time anomaly detection.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] In the oil and gas sector, anomaly detection is not just crucial for maintenance and safety, but also for environmental protection.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] Aljameel et al. propose an advanced machine learning-based model for detecting minor leaks in oil and gas pipelines, a task traditional methods may miss.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] Many anomaly detection techniques have been proposed in literature.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] The performance of methods usually depend on the data sets.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] For example, some may be suited to detecting local outliers, while others global, and methods have little systematic advantages over another when compared across many data sets.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] Almost all algorithms also require the setting of non-intuitive parameters critical for performance, and usually unknown before application.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] The size of bins are key to the effectiveness of this technique but must be determined by the implementer.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] A more sophisticated technique uses kernel functions to approximate the distribution of the normal data.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] Instances in low probability areas of the distribution are then considered anomalies.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] Quantum machine learning approaches have been investigated for anomaly detection on near-term quantum hardware.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] Quantum support vector machines (QSVMs) using quantum kernel methods, such as the ZZFeatureMap, have been applied to classification of normal versus anomalous instances by leveraging high-dimensional quantum feature spaces.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] Histogram-based Outlier Score (HBOS) uses value histograms and assumes feature independence for fast predictions.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] Dynamic networks, such as those representing financial systems, social media interactions, and transportation infrastructure, are subject to constant change, making anomaly detection within them a complex task.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] Unlike static graphs, dynamic networks reflect evolving relationships and states, requiring adaptive techniques for anomaly detection.
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] Many of the methods discussed above only yield an anomaly score prediction, which often can be explained to users as the point being in a region of low data density (or relatively low density compared to the neighbor's densities).
[src:threat-hunting/anomaly-detection] In explainable artificial intelligence, the users demand methods with higher explainability.
[src:threat-hunting/cyber-threat-hunting] In information security, **threat hunting** is the process of proactively searching for threats against computer systems in order to protect them.
[src:threat-hunting/cyber-threat-hunting] This is in contrast to traditional threat management measures, such as firewalls, intrusion detection systems (IDS), malware sandbox (computer security) and SIEM systems, which typically involve an investigation of evidence-based data *after* there has been a warning of a potential threat.
[src:threat-hunting/cyber-threat-hunting] Threat analyst Lesley Carhart stated that there is no consensus amongst practitioners what threat hunting actually entails.
[src:threat-hunting/cyber-threat-hunting] Recently, the world has seen a rise in the number and severity of cyber attacks, data breaches, malware infections, and online fraud incidents.
[src:threat-hunting/cyber-threat-hunting] According to cybersecurity and AI company SonicWall, the number of ransomware attacks grew by 105% globally.
[src:threat-hunting/cyber-threat-hunting] Major corporations around the world have fallen victim to high-profile data breaches, with the average cost of a data breach now estimated at $4.24 million, according to IBM.
[src:threat-hunting/cyber-threat-hunting] Threat hunting has traditionally been a manual process, in which a security analyst sifts through various data information using their own knowledge and familiarity with the network to create hypotheses about potential threats, such as, but not limited to, lateral movement by threat actors.
[src:threat-hunting/cyber-threat-hunting] To be even more effective and efficient, however, threat hunting can be partially automated, or machine-assisted, as well.
[src:threat-hunting/cyber-threat-hunting] In this case, the analyst uses software that leverages machine learning and user and entity behavior analytics (UEBA) to inform the analyst of potential risks.
[src:threat-hunting/cyber-threat-hunting] The analyst then investigates these potential risks, tracking suspicious behavior in the network.
[src:threat-hunting/cyber-threat-hunting] Thus, hunting is an iterative process, meaning that it must be continuously carried out in a loop, beginning with a hypothesis.
[src:threat-hunting/cyber-threat-hunting] The analysts research their hypothesis by going through vast amounts of data about the network.
[src:threat-hunting/cyber-threat-hunting] The results are then stored so that they can be used to improve the automated portion of the detection system and to serve as a foundation for future hypotheses.
[src:threat-hunting/cyber-threat-hunting] The Detection Maturity Level (DML) model expresses threat indicators can be detected at different semantic levels.
[src:threat-hunting/cyber-threat-hunting] High semantic indicators such as goal and strategy or tactics, techniques and procedures (TTPs) are more valuable to identify than low semantic indicators such as network artifacts and atomic indicators such as IP addresses.
[src:threat-hunting/cyber-threat-hunting] SIEM tools typically only provide indicators at relatively low semantic levels.
[src:threat-hunting/cyber-threat-hunting] There is therefore a need to develop SIEM tools that can provide threat indicators at higher semantic levels.
[src:threat-hunting/cyber-threat-hunting] Indicator of Concern - Using Open-source intelligence (OSINT), data can be collected from publicly available sources to be used for cyberattack detection and threat hunting.
[src:threat-hunting/cyber-threat-hunting] The dwell time either indicates the entire span of a security incident (initial compromise until detection and full cleanup) or the 'mean time to detect' (from initial compromise until detection).
[src:threat-hunting/cyber-threat-hunting] According to the 2022 Mandiant M-Trends Report, cyberattackers operate undetected for an average of 21 days (a 79% reduction, compared to 2016), but this varies greatly by region.
[src:threat-hunting/cyber-threat-hunting] Per Mandiant, the dwell time can be as low as 17 days (in the Americas) or as high as 48 days (in EMEA).
[src:threat-hunting/cyber-threat-hunting] The study also showed that 47% of attacks are discovered only after notification from an external party.
[src:threat-hunting/cyber-threat-hunting] Regulatory frameworks increasingly emphasize proactive threat detection as part of comprehensive security programs.
[src:threat-hunting/cyber-threat-hunting] The December 2024 HIPAA Security Rule NPRM proposed requiring regulated entities to deploy technology capable of detecting and responding to suspicious network activity, including continuous monitoring of information systems for unauthorized access attempts.
[src:threat-hunting/cyber-threat-hunting] The NIST Cybersecurity Framework 2.0 Detect function specifically addresses continuous monitoring and anomaly detection as foundational security activities.
[src:threat-hunting/indicator-of-compromise] An **indicator of compromise** (**IoC**) in computer forensics is an artifact observed on a computer network or within an operating system that, with high confidence, indicates a computer intrusion.
[src:threat-hunting/indicator-of-compromise] Common IoCs include virus signatures, suspicious IP addresses, MD5 hashes of malware files, and malicious URLs or domain names associated with botnet command-and-control servers.
[src:threat-hunting/indicator-of-compromise] Once IoCs are identified through incident response or forensic analysis, they can be used for early detection of future attacks with intrusion detection systems and antivirus software.
[src:threat-hunting/indicator-of-compromise] Known indicators are often exchanged within the cybersecurity industry, commonly using the Traffic Light Protocol (TLP) to indicate how information may be shared.
[src:threat-hunting/indicator-of-compromise] Other frameworks and standards are also used to support secure information sharing.
[src:threat-hunting/managed-detection-and-response] MDR aims to address the growing cybersecurity skills gap faced by many organizations and overwhelmed security teams dealing with increasing volumes of alerts.
[src:threat-hunting/managed-detection-and-response] It offers continuous threat monitoring, detection, investigation, and response by leveraging technologies like endpoint detection and response tools.
[src:threat-hunting/managed-detection-and-response] MDR involves outsourcing threat hunting and incident response functions to teams of cybersecurity experts at the provider.
[src:threat-hunting/managed-detection-and-response] It allows resource-constrained organizations to augment their security capabilities and address advanced, targeted cyberattacks and complex threats they may lack the in-house resources and skills to handle alone.
[src:threat-hunting/managed-detection-and-response] Key features of MDR include: 24/7 monitoring and analysis by security experts, investigation and prioritization of threats, detailed remediation recommendations, access to advanced tools and threat intelligence, ongoing threat-hunting services.
[src:threat-hunting/managed-detection-and-response] Gartner predicts that 50% of all enterprises will have adopted MDR services for their cybersecurity by 2025.
[src:threat-hunting/managed-detection-and-response] According to a report by the Fortune Business Insights of 2023, the MDR Market size is to reach 6.29 billion $ in 2030.
[src:threat-hunting/managed-detection-and-response] In 2025, two trend emerged in the MDR market : detection engineering and security posture management.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] In computer security, a **threat** is a potential negative action or event enabled by a vulnerability that results in an unwanted impact to a computer system or application.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] A threat can be either a negative "intentional" event like hacking or an "accidental" negative event or otherwise a circumstance, capability, action, or event (incident is often used as a blanket term).
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] A *threat actor* who is an individual or group that can perform the threat action, such as exploiting a vulnerability to actualise a negative impact.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] An *exploit* is a vulnerability that a threat actor used to cause an incident.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] A resource (both physical or logical) can have one or more vulnerabilities that can be exploited by a threat agent in a threat action.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] The result can potentially compromise the confidentiality, integrity or availability properties of resources (potentially different than the vulnerable one) of the organization and others involved parties (customers, suppliers).
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] The so-called CIA triad is the basis of information security.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] The attack can be *active* when it attempts to alter system resources or affect their operation: so it compromises Integrity or Availability.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] A "*passive attack*" attempts to learn or make use of information from the system but does not affect system resources: so it compromises Confidentiality.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] OWASP (see figure) depicts the same phenomenon in slightly different terms: a threat agent through an attack vector exploits a weakness (vulnerability) of the system and the related security controls causing a technical impact on an IT resource (asset) connected to a business impact.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] Countermeasures are also called security controls; when applied to the transmission of information are named security services.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] The overall picture represents the risk factors of the risk scenario.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] The widespread of computer dependencies and the consequent raising of the consequence of a successful attack, led to a new term cyberwarfare.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] Nowadays the many real attacks exploit Psychology at least as much as technology.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] Phishing and Pretexting and other methods are called social engineering techniques.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] The Web 2.0 applications, specifically Social network services, can be a mean to get in touch with people in charge of system administration or even system security, inducing them to reveal sensitive information.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] Note that a threat type can have multiple origins.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] Recent trends in computer threats show an increase in ransomware attacks, supply chain attacks, and fileless malware.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] Ransomware attacks involve the encryption of a victim's files and a demand for payment to restore access.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] Supply chain attacks target the weakest links in a supply chain to gain access to high-value targets.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] Fileless malware attacks use techniques that allow malware to run in memory, making it difficult to detect.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] Microsoft previously rated the risk of security threats using five categories in a classification called DREAD: Risk assessment model.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] The spread over a network of threats can lead to dangerous situations.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] In military and civil fields, threat level has been defined: for example INFOCON is a threat level used by the US.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] Leading antivirus software vendors publish global threat level on their websites.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] In cybersecurity and risk assessment, a threat actor (or *threat agents*, *attackers*, or *adversaries*) is a person, group, organisation, state, or other entity with the ability to cause, carry, transmit, support, or exploit a threat.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] Threat actors are commonly analysed according to their motivations, resources, technical capability, access to systems, relationship to a target, and degree of connection to state authority.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] They may exploit vulnerabilities, conduct social engineering, steal or monetise data, disrupt operations, or support other actors who carry out such activity.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] Because the term covers a wide range of actors, researchers and security organisations use taxonomies that distinguish between groups such as cybercriminals, state-linked actors, ideologically motivated actors, thrill seekers or trolls, insiders, and competitors.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] Threat actor classifications are used in risk management, cyber threat intelligence, and incident response to connect observed behaviour with possible objectives and likely future activity.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] The categories are not always mutually exclusive: the same actor may combine criminal, ideological, commercial, or state-linked motivations, and different organisations may use different names for similar actors.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] A collection of threats in a particular domain or context, with information on identified vulnerable assets, threats, risks, threat actors and observed trends.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] Threats should be managed by operating an ISMS, performing all the IT risk management activities foreseen by laws, standards and methodologies.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] Very large organizations tend to adopt business continuity management plans in order to protect, maintain and recover business-critical processes and systems.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] Some of these plans are implemented by computer security incident response team (CSIRT).
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] Threat management must identify, evaluate, and categorize threats.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] Many organizations perform only a subset of these methods, adopting countermeasures based on a non-systematic approach, resulting in *computer insecurity*.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] Information security awareness is a significant market.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] There has been a lot of software developed to deal with IT threats, including both open-source software and proprietary software.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] Threat management involves a wide variety of threats including physical threats like flood and fire.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] While ISMS risk assessment process does incorporate threat management for cyber threats such as remote buffer overflows the risk assessment process doesn't include processes such as threat intelligence management or response procedures.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] Cyber threat management (CTM) is emerging as the best practice for managing cyber threats beyond the basic risk assessment found in ISMS.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] It enables early identification of threats, data-driven situational awareness, accurate decision-making, and timely threat mitigating actions.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] The SANS Institute has conducted research and surveys on the effectiveness of threat hunting to track and disrupt cyber adversaries as early in their process as possible.
[src:threat-hunting/threat-computer-security] According to a survey performed in 2019, "61% [of the respondents] report at least an 11% measurable improvement in their overall security posture" and 23.6% of the respondents have experienced a 'significant improvement' in reducing the dwell time.
